    <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the cost of commercial kitchen plumbing in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Commercial kitchen plumbing costs range from ₹40,000–80,000 for a cloud kitchen to ₹2,50,000–6,50,000 for a large hotel kitchen. This includes water supply piping, drainage, grease trap, floor drains, hot water system, and labour. The biggest cost variables are kitchen size, number of equipment connection points, and whether the space has existing plumbing infrastructure or needs everything from scratch. In Tier-1 metros, expect 30–40% higher labour costs compared to Tier-2 cities.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Do I need a three-phase connection for a bakery in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, almost every commercial bakery in India needs a three-phase connection. Even a small bakery with a 2-deck electric oven (6–12 kW) and a planetary mixer (1–2 kW) exceeds the 5 kW threshold where three-phase becomes necessary. A three-phase connection for a bakery provides 415V supply, handles high startup currents from oven heating elements and mixer motors, and delivers more stable voltage than single-phase. Apply through your local DISCOM (BSES, MSEDCL, BESCOM, etc.) with a load estimate from a licensed electrical contractor. Connection charges range from ₹15,000 for 10 kW to ₹1,00,000+ for 50 kW, depending on your state.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Is a grease trap mandatory for restaurants in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, a grease trap is mandatory for all commercial food establishments in India that discharge wastewater into the municipal sewer system. This requirement comes from CPCB guidelines and is enforced by local municipal corporations. FSSAI inspectors also check for grease traps during license renewal inspections. A suitable grease trap for a small restaurant costs ₹12,000–25,000 installed. Failing to install one can result in fines of ₹10,000–50,000, sewer line blockages that affect neighbouring properties, and potential issues with your FSSAI license renewal.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What size pipe is needed for commercial kitchen drainage?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Use minimum 75mm PVC pipes for branch drain lines and 110mm for the main drain line in small to medium commercial kitchens. Large hotel and banquet kitchens should use 110mm throughout, with 160mm for the main outgoing line. All drain pipes must maintain a minimum slope of 1:40 (2.5%) for proper gravity flow. Use SS grating covers on floor drains — plastic grating cracks under commercial kitchen conditions and hot water exposure.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How much does a three-phase electrical connection cost in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A commercial three-phase connection in India costs ₹15,000–40,000 for a 10–20 kW sanctioned load, ₹40,000–1,00,000 for 20–50 kW, and ₹1,00,000–2,50,000 for 50–100 kW. These charges include the DISCOM connection fee, security deposit, and meter. Loads above 100 kW require a High Tension (HT) connection with a dedicated transformer, costing ₹3,00,000 or more. These are DISCOM charges only — internal wiring, panel, and earthing are additional. The total electrical infrastructure cost (connection + internal work) ranges from ₹40,000–80,000 for a cloud kitchen to ₹2,25,000–6,30,000 for a large hotel kitchen.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">LPG vs PNG — which is better for a commercial kitchen?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">PNG (Piped Natural Gas) is better for commercial kitchens where available. It's 30–40% cheaper than commercial LPG per unit of heat, provides continuous supply without cylinder changeovers, and is inherently safer because natural gas is lighter than air and disperses upward in case of a leak. The connection cost (₹20,000–50,000) pays back within 8–14 months through fuel savings. However, PNG is only available in select cities through CGD companies (IGL in Delhi, MGL in Mumbai, etc.). If PNG isn't available in your area, use commercial LPG with a proper manifold system, gas leak detectors, and authorised cylinder supply — never domestic cylinders for commercial use.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What electrical safety equipment is required in a commercial kitchen?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Every commercial kitchen in India must have: (1) RCCB protection — 30mA sensitivity for all socket and equipment circuits to prevent electrocution, (2) appropriately rated MCBs on every circuit — C-curve for motor loads, B-curve for lighting and sockets, (3) proper earthing with minimum 2 earth pits and earth resistance below 1 ohm, (4) surge protection device (SPD) in the distribution panel, and (5) equipotential bonding of all metal equipment to the earthing system. Additionally, you need ABC-type fire extinguishers, a fire blanket near cooking stations, and gas leak detectors with auto-shutoff if using LPG or PNG. All electrical work must comply with IS 732 (wiring) and IS 3043 (earthing).</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How often should grease traps and earthing be maintained?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Grease traps should be cleaned every 2–4 weeks depending on kitchen volume. A small restaurant can go 3–4 weeks; a busy hotel kitchen may need weekly cleaning. Schedule a plumber AMC (₹1,500–3,000/month) if you don't want to handle it in-house. For earthing, test earth resistance annually using a Megger tester — the reading must be below 1 ohm. During dry summer months, earth resistance rises; you may need to water the earth pits or add salt/charcoal to maintain conductivity. Chemical earthing systems are maintenance-free and recommended for areas with dry or sandy soil.</div>
    </div>

